Kahoot questions (ADVC):
Question:
What limits how low we can reduce the voltage in a chip?

A. The chip must use less memory.
B. The clock frequency must stay exactly constant.
C. The critical path must still finish within one clock cycle. (correct)
D. The battery voltage must be higher than the core voltage.

Question:
Why do real chips usually not operate all the way down at the Minimum Energy Point?

A. Because the chip would consume too much dynamic power.
B. Because voltage that low can cause reliability performance problems. (correct)
C. Because below a certain voltage, the power saved becomes negligible.
D. Because the chip no longer needs adaptive voltage control.

Question:
What is one advantage of dynamic voltage control, such as ADVC, compared to using fixed safety margins?

A. It makes every chip run at the exact same voltage.
B. It removes the need for timing checks.
C. It can choose a voltage for each specific chip instead of using one worst-case voltage for all chips. (correct)
D. It increases the clock period automatically.

Question:
How do we know that the in-line DLL delay has been matched to the critical path delay?

A. When the DLL is completely bypassed.
B. When the chip reaches its maximum possible frequency.
C. When the total measured delay becomes twice the original delay measured with the DLL bypassed. (correct)
D. When the voltage reaches the Minimum Energy Point.

Question:
What is the role of the First-Fail mechanism in ADVC?

A. To increase the chip’s clock frequency automatically.
B. To determine the delay of the critical path of the chip.
C. To find the minimum voltage where the chip can still meet timing for the selected frequency. (correct)
D. To keep the chip at one fixed worst-case voltage.

Question:
When should the first fail sensor be used?

A. Every time the user changes the clock frequency.
B. Whenever there is a significant change of temperature.
C. Whenever the user turn on/off a clock.
D. All of the above. (correct)



